get.description:
## Debugging ##

### Session Resolution + ORM Lazy Loading ###

> *`Parent instance [...] is not bound to a Session`* - [**Official Documentation**](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/13/errors.html#parent-instance-x-is-not-bound-to-a-session-lazy-load-deferred-load-refresh-etc-operation-cannot-proceed)

-   The most common error message when dealing with the ORM, and it occurs as a

    result of the nature of a technique the ORM makes wide use of known as lazy

    loading.

-   Lazy loading is a common object-relational pattern whereby an object thatâ€™s

    persisted.
    by the ORM maintains a proxy to the database itself, such that when various

    attributes upon the object are accessed, their value may be retrieved from the

    database lazily. The advantage to this approach is that objects can be retrieved

    from the database without having to load all of their attributes or related data

    at once, and instead only that data which is requested can be delivered at that

    time.

-   The major disadvantage is basically a mirror image of the advantage, which

    is that if lots of objects are being loaded which are known to require a certain

    set of data in all cases, it is wasteful to load that additional data piecemeal.

post.description:
# Users - Provisioning #

*Create an Application, API User Database Record.*

**Data is `POST`'ed via JSON-Serialized Input.**

Attributes:
- `Username`: Primary Account Name, Unique

- `Email-Address`: Associated Account's Registration Email Address

- `Preferred-Name`: Nickname, Display-Name

- `Active`: Account Status

- `Gender-Code`: Gender Identity via ISO International Standard Code(s)

- `Password`: Pepper + Salted, Hashed Account Sign-In String


Object Types:
- `Name`: ***Account, User Full-Name***. Properties:

    - `First` (String)

    - `Middle` (String)

    - `Last` (String)

- `Verification`: ***User's Account Verification Status***. Properties:

    - `Verified`: (Boolean)

- `Company`: ***User's Associated Company Login***. Properties:

    - `Name`: (String), **Unique**

    - `Type`: (String), **Unique**, Enumeration of [`Medical`, `Construction`, `Entertainment`, `Transportation`, `Security`, `Consulting`, `Hospitality`, `Automobile`, `Estate`, `Finance`, `Insurance`, `Oil`, `Mining`, `Energy`, `Engineering`, `Electronics`, `Legal`, `Telecommunications`, `Retail`, `Education`, `Storage`, `Textiles`, `Agriculture`, `Manufacturing`, `Gaming`].

    - `Website`: (HTTP(s), String), **Unique**

    - `Name`: (String), **Unique**

- `Unit`: (String)

- `Note`: ...

put.description:
# [Nexus] User Record Update(s) #

> ***Update an Established Database User Record***

One of three *Unique* keys must be provided in order to locate any
given, single record:

- `ID` -- **User.ID**, `UUID`

- `Username` -- **User.Username**, `String`

- `Email` -- **User.Email**, `String`

*Any and All* Unique keys can be provided; however, in exception to `ID`,
if either Email or Username are established in addition to other Unique
keys, they may be over-written if they differ from the record's
previous content.

Value(s) intentionally unset will ***not*** get updated.

## User API Token ##

*Note* - When Updating a User's `Token`, simply set to `True` to programatically
generate a new `Token`. Manual overrides are not allowed and such is
intentionally limited to `True`, `False`, or `NULL`.

## Gender Codes ##

> *Please see [ISO5218 Gender Codes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_5218) for more
> information.*

- Empty:    `0x0`

- Male:     `0x1`

- Female:   `0x2`

- Other:    `0x9`

```bash
export URL="http://localhost:3000/API/AGILE/Scrum/Update?ID=6aa2821c-8898-4afe-aa8c-4fe8f336d97b"

curl -X "PUT" "${URL}" \
    --header "accept: application/json" \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --data '{
        "UID": "string",
        "Synopsis": "string",
        "Projection": "string",
        "Complication": "string",
        "Note": {
            "Content": "...",
            "Internal": false
        },
        "Day": 6,
        "Week": 10,
        "Year": 2021
    }'
```
